                        <div id="content" class="hfeed">
                            <article class="post-155580 post type-post status-publish hentry category-private-lives tag-cellular-telephones tag-grief-emotion tag-voice-mail des-cellular-telephones des-grief-emotion des-voice-mail news_keywords-grief-2 news_keywords-mobile-phone news_keywords-voice-mail-2"
                                id="post-155580">
                                <header class="postHeader">
                                    <div class="postKicker">
                                        <span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/?module=BlogCategory&amp;version=Blog Post&amp;action=Click&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Header">Private Lives</a></span>
                                    </div>
                                    <h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">This Is Your Grandmother</h1>
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer">
                                        <address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Rebecca Scherm			</address>
                                        <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-01-21T23:07:01+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">January 21, 2015 6:07 pm</time>
                                        <!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">January 21, 2015 6:07 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
                                    </div>
                                </header>
                                <div class="entry-content">
                                    <div class="inlineModule">
                                        <div class="entry">
                                            <div class="thumb"><img alt="Private Lives" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/firstperson/firstperson45.png" width="50" height="50"></div>
                                            <p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/">Private Lives:</a> Personal essays on the news of the world and the news of our lives.
                                            </p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">ANN ARBOR &#x2014; I had two saved messages, and both began the same way: &#x201C;Hello, Rebecca. This is your grandmother. In Florida.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the first message, she still sounded fully herself. Her voice was the strangest music. She had a Julia Child-like range, full of low sweeps, squawks and shrieks, but with a cranky and guttural scoff and dismissal.
                                        Imagine Katharine Hepburn at the Wendy&#x2019;s drive-through. She asked for &#x201C;tomahto&#x201D; on her &#x201C;haaamburger,&#x201D; leaning nasally into that <em>ham</em>. Also, &#x201C;fiah-house,&#x201D;
                                        as in &#x201C;Where would I ever wear that, to play bridge at the fiah-house?&#x201D; I was Rebeccer, always. And close the refridge! </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I&#x2019;d begun to save each of her messages on my cellphone until I got the next, having realized that any message could be the last. She was in the early stages of dementia, and when I answered or called her back,
                                        she was often too tired to talk, so these messages became our conversation. <span id="more-155580"></span></p>
                                    <div class="w480">
                                        <figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/01/22/opinion/22PRIVATE/22PRIVATE-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
                                            <div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/01/22/opinion/22PRIVATE/22PRIVATE-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/01/22/opinion/22PRIVATE/22PRIVATE-blog480.jpg" id="100000003463598"
                                                    width="480" height="638" alt="">
                                                <meta itemprop="height" content="638">
                                                <meta itemprop="width" content="480">
                                            </div>
                                            <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Cristina Span&#xF2;</span>
                                            </figcaption>
                                        </figure>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the second message, she sounded like a tentative actress at a reading for my grandmother&#x2019;s memoirs. &#x201C;Hello, Rebeccer? This is your grandmotha? In Florida?&#x201D; As though she herself were not sure.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">She had tried to prepare me for her death for years: &#x201C;When I die &#x2026; &#x201D; Of course, I was unprepared. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But I had these messages. I could still listen to her. Every month or so, my voice mail robot would announce that they were &#x201C;due for automatic deletion,&#x201D; as though accusing me of being morbid or too sentimental.
                                        &#x201C;You must re-save to prevent automatic deletion.&#x201D; Oh, how I saved and resaved! I listened to the first message about once a week. The second one was often a little too rough, and I&#x2019;d just press
                                        save and get on with it. &#x201C;Get on with it&#x201D; was one of my grandmother&#x2019;s key sayings, key tenets. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ahh, I miss her something awful &#x2014; there she is again &#x2014; but at least I had her voice. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In February, I left the country for a month. No phone. When I came back, all my saved messages were gone. At first, bleary from a night of red-eye flights, I thought I&#x2019;d misunderstood, that they were in there,
                                        somewhere. I took a nap. I went through the mail, I did laundry. I picked up the phone again. They were gone. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I tried to shrug it off. I&#x2019;d had that first message for a year, after all &#x2014; long enough, my grandmother would say, her chin imperiously raised. I still had cards with her handwriting, photographs, some
                                        plastic bracelets. And the beginnings of the messages were preserved in the perfect hi-fidelity of my mind. &#x201C;Hello, Rebeccer. This is your grandmotha. In Florida.&#x201D; But I couldn&#x2019;t remember what
                                        she said after. I looked at my phone. Wasn&#x2019;t the point of all this technology to better connect us to our loved ones? Surely, in 2014, with our correspondence under constant surveillance by spies both public
                                        and private, there were no lost messages anymore. I became indignant, my own chin imperiously raised.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I went to my phone company&#x2019;s website and requested support via live chat, explaining that I&#x2019;d just come back from a trip to find that all my saved voice mails were gone, and would it be possible for me
                                        to retrieve them? A representative named &#x201C;Elron E&#x201D; responded:</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Oh my, I apologize if this has been causing you inconvenience; nothing to worry about, we hope to have a resolution with your messages&#x2019; issue.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After half an hour, once I had satisfied Elron that I had not deleted them myself, he confided:</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;I have known the issue you have now Rebecca&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;The T-Mobile Voicemail system is designed to automatically delete messages in the voicemail system after a specific period of time, depending on if they have been played or not. This delete time is dependent
                                        on the type of voicemail box the customer has on the account.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Yes,&#x201D; I typed back, &#x201C;but it usually asks me. My fear, as I said, is that because I went a month without phone, it deleted them without asking.&#x201D; </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Elron E: &#x201C;But do not worry. we have a work around for you&#x201D; </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Me: &#x201C;great!&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Elron directed me into the cloud, where he was sure my messages would be waiting for me. Every time I&#x2019;d pressed 9, I had reasserted their importance. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Me: &#x201C;they aren&#x2019;t there&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Elron E: &#x201C;I got you. Well, that is the only way for us to retrieve your saved voicemails.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Me: &#x201C;so you are telling me that they were not saved anywhere despite my saving them many times.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The pattern of this conversation felt pitifully familiar: a flight is canceled without explanation; a procedure that was covered by insurance suddenly isn&#x2019;t. The representative begins helpfully, and the consumer
                                        is optimistic and polite, understanding that this is not the representative&#x2019;s fault. Then the representative says that he or she cannot help. The representative becomes representative &#x2014; of the company,
                                        of the failings of all technologies, of everyone who&#x2019;s ever disappointed you, of your own failure to predict what would go wrong. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;I am afraid so Rebecca,&#x201D; Elron told me.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I remember my shock, as a child, at the outlandish rage of grown-ups having tantrums &#x2014; meltdowns at the post-office, screaming hysteria at the airline counter &#x2014; and my parents wincing in empathy. That
                                        guy is having a bad day, they would say. Probably his wife just left him or he was laid off, and now he&#x2019;s taking it out on somebody else. Forgive him, but remember not to do that yourself. Remember how embarrassing
                                        it is. Remember that this is not Elron E&#x2019;s fault. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That&#x2019;s when Elron wrote, &#x201C;Well, I hope that this would serve as a lesson for us to do back up of files to avoid this to happen again.&#x201D; </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">All my self-awareness evaporated. I was livid. I knew that I was bundling my real grief at never hearing my grandmother&#x2019;s voice again into the sorriest symbol of it, the consumer complaint. Such a thin sack to
                                        carry something so large, but sometimes it&#x2019;s all you have. In the choice between grief and anger, anger seems to cost so much less. How dare Elron E lecture me, when all he had done was confirm that the voice
                                        mails from my dead grandmother had indeed fallen into the void of digital nothing?</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Me: &#x201C;Well, this was not helpful. You tried, but you were not able to help me get these messages that should not have been deleted. They were from someone close to me who has since died. And I&#x2019;m very upset
                                        about that. So please do more than suggest it is a good lesson.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Elron E: &#x201C;I understand, If there was a way for me to get those messages back, I would have done it for you, I am sincerely sorry, I know that those messages mean alot to you.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What was I doing, airing my grief to Elron E? I was incensed by his hand-patting, even though I had given him no alternative. I did some quick and ugly emotional arithmetic and saw what was possible and what wasn&#x2019;t,
                                        and yet I wanted some kind of real acknowledgment of my real sadness, which by mentioning to a strange representative on the Internet, I had already cheapened. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Me: &#x201C;Let&#x2019;s take my grief out of it. My tmobile product malfunctioned by not saving messages to my tmobile that it should have. How will you, at the very least, compensate me for this?&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Elron E: &#x201C;Rebecca, with this one, I can provide $10 to be off on your bill as compensation for the deleted Voicemail you have.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I shut my computer and walked away, disgusted with Elron E and all representatives tasked with paying off our despair, inappropriately expressed, with $10 discount vouchers. But mostly with myself. I felt far, far worse
                                        than I had before I&#x2019;d asked for help. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A few minutes later, my phone rang. It was Elron E&#x2019;s supervisor, wanting to know why I had abandoned our chat. &#x201C;I am sorry you could not recover your deleted voice mail messages,&#x201D; she began.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Excuse me,&#x201D; I interrupted her. &#x201C;I want to be clear &#x2014; these were not deleted voice mails. I never deleted them. I had resaved them dozens of times. Your technology failed to store them as
                                        it was supposed to, and then the safeguards you have against accidental-yet-automatic deletion also failed. But I did not delete them.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Yes,&#x201D; she said, &#x201C;and is there anything else I can help you with today?&#x201D;</p>
                                    <hr>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><a href="//www.rebeccascherm.com/">Rebecca Scherm</a> is the author of the novel &#x201C;Unbecoming.&#x201D; </em></p>
                                    <footer class="story-footer">
                                        <div class="story-meta">
                                            <p class="story-print-citation">A version of this article appears in print on 01/25/2015, on page <span itemprop="printSection">SR</span><span itemprop="printPage">8</span> of the <span itemprop="printEdition">National</span> edition with
                                                the headline: This Is Your Grandmother Calling.</p>
                                        </div>
                                    </footer>
                                </div>
